{"website": "http://web.archive.org/web/20200529015237id_/https://www.kroger.com/hc/help/faqs/covid-19/general", "text": "\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--Kroger - COVID-19 FAQs--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--Skip to content--sep--Sign In--sep--Popular--sep--Buy 5, Save $1 Each--sep--Ways to Shop--sep--Weekly Ad--sep--Digital Coupons--sep--My Prescriptions--sep--Departments--sep--Summer Shop--sep--At Home--sep--Father's Day Shop--sep--Graduation Shop--sep--Meat and Seafood--sep--Fresh Fruit and Vegetables--sep--Pantry--sep--Natural and Organic--sep--Dairy and Eggs--sep--Floral--sep--Frozen--sep--Deli--sep--Bakery--sep--Beer, Wine and Liquor--sep--Candy--sep--Home and Electronics--sep--Cleaning and Household--sep--Health and Wellness--sep--Beauty--sep--Personal Care--sep--Vitamins and Supplements--sep--Baby--sep--Pet--sep--Ship to Home--sep--Specialty Diets--sep--International Cuisine--sep--Fred Meyer Jewelers--sep--Savings--sep--Shop by Brand--sep--Discover--sep--Pharmacy and Health--sep--Money and Perks--sep--Search--sep--Clear--sep--Ship to--sep--\u00a0--sep--95050--sep-- --sep--Locations--sep--Sign In--sep--Cart--sep--Gift Cards--sep--Lists--sep--Weekly Ad--sep--Digital Coupons--sep--Our Payment Cards--sep--Help--sep--Breadcrumb--sep--Help Center--sep--FAQs--sep--COVID-19 - General--sep--General FAQs--sep--COVID-19--sep--General--sep--COVID-19--sep--General--sep--Questions and Answers--sep--Expand All--sep--Are you limiting customer capacity in stores?--sep--As an essential business, we are committed to doing our part to flatten the curve while providing our customers with access to fresh, affordable food. To further encourage physical distancing, we will begin limiting the number of people in our stores at a time to 50% or more of the building code\u2019s calculated capacity. QueVision, our industry-leading technology system that uses sensors and predictive analytics, will help us to monitor traffic flow in and out of the store.--sep--What happens if a store reaches capacity?--sep--Over the last few weeks, customers\u2019 shopping patterns and frequency have changed, so we do not anticipate our stores reaching capacity often. When and if it happens, QueVision will alert us and an associate will direct customers to form a line outside the store, encouraging six feet between each customer. As customers exit the store, additional customers will be able to enter the store. --sep--Are you limiting purchase quantities?--sep--We have set purchase limits on certain categories of items that are in high demand. These purchase limits will also be applied to orders placed on our app or website. This is to ensure that all customers have access to the items they need most.--sep--Will you have special hours for senior citizens?--sep--In some areas, we\u2019re now opening one hour early, to enable senior citizens and other high-risk groups to shop before we open to the public. We\u2019ll continue to evaluate these special hours and make changes as we learn more. You can find the most up-to-date information about your store --sep--here--sep--. --sep--How are you maintaining product availability?--sep--Our supply chain associates are working tirelessly to replenish our stores daily with the items our customers need most. --sep--Has your return policy changed?--sep--For health and safety reasons, we are not currently accepting returns on items purchased in excess that our customers no longer want.--sep--Why did store hours change?--sep--Our modified store hours give our associates the time they need to clean and restock shelves. You can find more information --sep--here--sep--.  --sep--What are you doing to increase pickup and delivery availability?--sep--We\u2019re making more timeslots available to accommodate the increase in demand for our pickup and delivery services. We\u2019ll continue to monitor and make changes as necessary to make pickup and delivery more accessible for our customers.--sep--Does your website show current product inventory?--sep--Pickup & Delivery:--sep-- Inventory varies by store and changes throughout the day as customers shop in-store and online. Inventory is not updated in real time. If an item shows that it\u2019s available for pickup or delivery, availability is not guaranteed. --sep--Ship:--sep-- Our shippable inventory is updated in near-real time. We encourage customers to check our app or website to view item availability. --sep--Unfortunately, our Customer Connect associates do not have insight into item availability. Our app or website is the best source for this information.--sep--What are you doing to protect and support your associates during this time?--sep--The past few weeks have been unprecedented for our country, our associates and our customers. Associates in our stores, warehouses, distribution centers, food production facilities and offices are working around the clock to keep our stores clean, open and stocked.--sep--On March 14, we created a policy allowing paid time off for associates diagnosed with COVID-19 or placed under quarantine. All eligible associates will receive their standard pay for up to 14 days. We have also made additional financial resources available through our --sep--Helping Hands--sep-- fund.  --sep--Can I have groceries delivered to my home without coming into contact with a shopper or driver?--sep--Yes, this option is available at online checkout on delivery orders. Simply choose the --sep--Leave at My Door--sep-- option and check the box next to \"I accept that I do not need to be present when my groceries are delivered.\u201d--sep--Why has the rain check policy been suspended?--sep--Due to current and ongoing product availability issues, we are not able to guarantee in-stock conditions on many items. We will not be issuing rain checks on out-of-stock items until further notice. We appreciate your understanding as we work to keep your store clean, open and stocked to the best of our abilities during this time.--sep--Preparedness, Store Conditions and Products--sep--How is The Kroger Co. handling this unprecedented pandemic?--sep--Our task force has coordinated organizational activities to help our business navigate through this public health event and quickly activate our COVID-19 preparedness plan. We also continue to partner with and follow guidance from federal, state and local agencies, including the CDC and other health organizations.--sep--What shopping options are currently available?--sep--Our associates are working to ensure our in-store, pickup, delivery and ship services are operational and available to customers. --sep--Have stores reduced their operating hours?--sep--In some areas, we have adjusted store operating hours to allow our associates more time to rest, clean and stock. You can view our updated operating hours --sep--here--sep--.--sep--Have stores implemented special operating hours for seniors and higher-risk populations?--sep--We appreciate the concern and care our customers are expressing for senior shoppers and higher-risk customers. All customers deserve to have access to affordable, fresh food and essentials. We're offering special hours for senior shoppers in several cities across the country. We have also been inspired to see local communities working together to shop on behalf of seniors and other higher-risk customers.--sep--We are asking our customers be patient, to be kind to one another and our associates, and to shop responsibly and purchase what you need, knowing that we will continue to replenish stores daily with the supplies and products our customers need most. --sep--Are you waiving check-cashing fees?--sep--Starting April 24, the Kroger Family of Companies is supporting the CARES Act by temporarily waiving the check-cashing fee for government-issued checks. --sep--Are Kroger Customers Required to Wear Masks?--sep--We encourage all our customers to wear a mask when they visit our stores, or alternatively, consider one of our ecommerce options available at kroger.com.--sep--Is free pickup service being offered?--sep--Our purpose is to Feed the Human Spirit, and we are always here for our customers and communities when they need us most, especially in times of uncertainty. --sep--We have experienced an increase in demand for our pickup service as customers seek alternative ways to shop for groceries. So, starting March 23, we are temporarily waiving our pickup service fee nationwide (a value of $4.95), with no minimum order threshold. Because of the surge, our customers may experience limited inventory options and longer wait times than usual. We appreciate our customers\u2019 understanding as we work tirelessly to serve the community during this unprecedented time. --sep--Can customers use SNAP benefits for pickup?--sep--The Kroger Family of Companies has rolled out the acceptance of Supplemental Nutrition Assistance Program (SNAP) benefits for Pickup across the country, with an estimated completion by the end of April. The low-contact, convenient service allows customers to shop online for groceries and pick up their order curbside.--sep-- How Pickup Works:--sep--Choose your preferred store location online or via the app--sep--Shop and place your order for groceries online or via the app--sep--Select a pickup date and time and SNAP/EBT as the payment method. If you\u2019re using an EBT card, you\u2019ll present your payment method at the time of pick up--sep--An associate shops for your order--sep--When it\u2019s time to pick up your order, look for the pickup signs in the store\u2019s parking lot and pull into your parking spot then call the number on the sign to let an associate know you\u2019ve arrived--sep--An associate will bring your order out and load it into your car. At this time, EBT card customers can complete their transaction via a mobile point-of-sale system and pay for ineligible EBT purchases or any remaining balance with their debit or credit card--sep--What about pickup-only stores?--sep--We continue to experience an increase in demand for our pickup service as customers seek alternative ways to shop for groceries. To support the increase, Kroger introduced its first pickup-only location in Cincinnati on March 25. --sep--Customers can select the Mt. Carmel Kroger (4630 Aicholtz Road, Cincinnati) as their preferred pickup location when placing their order on --sep--kroger.com--sep-- or through the app. Pickup will be available from 8 a.m. to 8 p.m. daily. As the location will no longer offer in-store shopping, associates will be fully focused on fulfilling pickup orders. The store\u2019s pharmacy will remain open and customers can speak directly with health care staff or pick up prescriptions. --sep--Are stores offering contact-free checkout options?--sep--To help customers shop safely and quickly, we are in the process of rolling out the improved Scan, Bag, Go mobile app nationwide. Customers using the feature can bring their clean reusable bags to the store where permissible \u2013 or use bags available at the store \u2013 to shop, scan and bag their groceries as they go. When a customer completes their shopping trip, they can pay with their phone, allowing them to bypass the traditional checkout process.--sep--Kroger Pay--sep-- is another capability within the mobile app that provides a contactless payment solution, simplifying the checkout and payment process for customers. The capability is available in several markets.--sep--We also offer a no-contact delivery option, low-contact pickup service and ship-to-home offering for pantry essentials.--sep--Have stores implemented product purchase limits?--sep--We have implemented product purchase limits on highly popular products to help ensure all our customers have access to them. Our manufacturing plants and suppliers are working tirelessly to help replenish our inventories. --sep--Should customers anticipate increased product prices?--sep--We are committed to customers having access to fresh and affordable food. Because of increased demand and limited inventory of some products, customers may experience price increases on commodities like eggs and meat.--sep--Is there a new return policy?--sep--We are temporarily suspending product returns to protect the health and wellbeing of our associates, customers and communities during the COVID-19 pandemic. If any fresh produce, meat, seafood or deli product does not meet our Fresh for Everyone standard, we will replace it or issue a refund. You can learn more about our return policy --sep--here--sep--. --sep--Can customers bring reusable bags?--sep--We continue to allow our customers to use reusable shopping bags, provided there is not a state or local ordinance that prohibits use. --sep--Should customers be concerned about the transmission of COVID-19 through food?--sep--The health and wellbeing of our associates, customers and communities is our top priority. The CDC has not provided guidance that food is a vehicle for virus transmission. If the CDC provides new guidance, we will follow it.--sep--What about the transmission of COVID-19 through imported goods?--sep--Most of our products are domestically sourced. Additionally, there\u2019s no evidence at this time of any coronavirus diagnoses related to imported goods.--sep--How does The Kroger Co. anticipate this event impacting its business?--sep--It\u2019s too early to tell the effect on our business. The event is not currently included in our guidance for 2020. Relative to others in the market we have limited supply chain exposure in China as most of the product we source is domestic.--sep--Are you hiring?--sep--The Kroger Co. has recently provided new career opportunities to more than 80,000 workers nationwide, including those from the hardest-hit sectors like restaurants, hotels and food service distributors. We plan to hire additional workers over the next several weeks to help us to continue to provide fresh food and useful supplies to communities across the country during the COVID-19 pandemic. Candidates may apply via --sep--jobs.kroger.com--sep-- and could be placed for employment within several days of applying. Kroger\u2019s average hourly wage is $15 an hour. And with comprehensive benefits factored in, our average hourly rate is over $20.--sep--Health and Wellbeing--sep--How are associates being recognized and rewarded?--sep--On March 21, we announced a one-time bonus for every hourly frontline grocery, supply chain, manufacturing and customer service associate, amounting to $300 for every full-time associate and $150 for every part-time associate.--sep--On March 31, we announced an additional Hero Bonus for all hourly frontline associates \u2013 a $2 premium above their standard base rate of pay, applied to hours worked March 29 through April 18. The premium will be disbursed weekly to ensure associates have access to additional cash.--sep--On April 16, we announced the extension of our Hero Bonus for all hourly frontline associates through May 2.--sep--What are you doing to protect customers and associates?--sep--We are taking these steps to protect our customers and associates: --sep--In Our Stores--sep--Cleaning commonly used areas more often, including cashier stations, self-checkouts, credit card terminals, conveyor belts and food service counters, and cleaning shelves when restocking products.--sep--Sanitizing restrooms more frequently and restocking with supplies, including soap, paper towels and hand sanitizer.--sep--Adding extra hand sanitizer at cashier stations, food service counters, and all Pharmacy, The Little Clinic and Starbucks locations.--sep--Wiping down shopping carts, baskets and equipment. --sep--Partnering with our suppliers to replenish high-demand preparedness products.--sep--Continuing to provide our customers with free disinfectant wipes at our store entrances to sanitize their shopping carts or baskets.--sep--Continuing to expand pickup and delivery services and contactless payment solutions like --sep--Kroger Pay--sep--.--sep--Maintaining industry-leading best practices for safe food handling. --sep--For Our Customers--sep--Encouraging our customers and associates to follow the CDC's suggested hygiene practices to reduce the spread of the virus.--sep--Recommending that our customers also practice safe food handling at home.--sep--Inviting customers to wear protective masks in our stores. --sep--For Our Associates --sep--We have supplied and are requiring our associates to wear protective masks. --sep--The Kroger Family of Companies and the UFCW--sep-- are calling on federal and state government leaders to take swift action to designate associates at grocery stores as \"extended first responders\" or \"emergency personnel\" to help receive priority access to protective masks and other benefits. --sep--We are installing plexiglass partitions at many cash registers, to further promote physical distancing. In addition, we are adding educational floor decals to promote physical distancing at checklanes and other counters.--sep--We are encouraging our associates to closely monitor their health and if they exhibit flu-like symptoms (fever, cough, sore throat, body aches, headache, chills, and fatigue) at work, they should go home and contact their doctor. If an associate has flu-like symptoms at home, they should not come to work. --sep--The Kroger Family of Companies and the UFCW--sep-- are calling on federal and state government leaders to take swift action to designate associates at grocery stores as \"extended first responders\" or \"emergency personnel\" to help receive priority access to protective masks and other benefits.    --sep--Kroger has enacted Emergency Leave Guidelines, allowing paid time off for associates diagnosed with COVID-19, placed under mandatory quarantine by their medical provider because of COVID-19 and paid time off for self-isolation and symptoms as verified by an accredited health care professional. All eligible associates will receive their standard pay for up to two weeks (14 days).--sep--For those affected by COVID-19, the organization has also made $5 million available through the Kroger Family of Companies Helping Hands fund to provide financial assistance to associates who face hardship due to COVID-19, including lack of access to childcare and for those considered higher-risk.--sep--We are providing access to mental health services and other benefits to support associates' mental and physical well-being during this stressful time. We\u2019re also offering an associate hotline to ensure benefit questions are answered quickly. --sep--At this time, we have extended our work-from-home policy for all associates in our corporate and division offices until at least May 31. We will continue to closely evaluate and adjust our policies accordingly. When the time is right to safely reopen our offices, it will be through a phased approach. --sep--Are Kroger Associates Required to Wear Personal Protective Equipment (PPE)?--sep--As an essential business, we\u2019ve been balancing our most urgent priority to provide a safe environment for our associates and customers with open stores, ecommerce solutions and an efficiently operating supply chain, so that our communities always have access to fresh, affordable food and products. --sep--We have provided masks for all our store associates to wear, and starting on April 26, we\u2019ll be requiring associates to wear them, in locations where they are not already mandated. Our associates are also welcome to bring their own suitable masks or facial coverings to work, if they prefer.--sep--We recognize that some associates, due to medical reasons or other circumstances, may not be able to wear a mask. Such situations will be addressed on a case-by-case basis. We are sourcing face shields to provide to those associates and will also explore other potential options, as needed.--sep--We also continue to enhance our daily sanitation practices, including cleaning commonly used areas more often like cashier stations, self-checkouts, credit card terminals, food service counters and shelves. --sep--We\u2019ve installed plexiglass partitions at many check lanes, including pharmacy and Starbucks registers, to further promote physical distancing. In addition, we\u2019ve installed educational floor decals to promote physical distancing at check lanes and other counters. --sep--Additionally, we\u2019ve adjusted store operating hours across the country to allow more time for our associates to rest, clean and replenish inventory.--sep--We believe all these steps will help to ensure the safety of our associates and help our communities to flatten the curve while at the same time meeting our obligation to be there for our customers.  --sep--Are Pharmacy and The Little Clinic locations being managed differently?--sep--Because many of our pharmacy or The Little Clinic customers may be visiting us for treatment of an illness, or to fill a prescription for one, our clinics and pharmacies are kept on separate air filtration systems from the rest of the store, which safeguards against germs potentially being spread around the rest of the store, and keeps fresh air circulating throughout. In addition, pharmacies and clinics are always set apart from fresh food areas, such as produce, bakery, and meat and seafood.--sep--All our pharmacists, technicians, clinicians, and patient care technicians follow the strictest rules of infection control. All pharmacies and clinics are cleaned routinely throughout the day with hospital grade sanitation products. During times of extraordinary concern, additional measures are taken.--sep--Are any Pharmacies or The Little Clinic locations offering COVID-19 drive-thru testing?--sep--We have formed partnerships with local and state offices and groups in Colorado, Kentucky, Indiana, Michigan, Ohio and Tennessee to support drive-thru COVID-19 testing. Learn more here.--sep--On April 27, Kroger Health announced plans to expand its drive-thru COVID-19 testing model to 50 locations in more than 12 states to perform up to 100,000 tests by the end of May. We will soon announce the additional states. Americans can access Kroger Health\u2019s free virtual screening tool to determine if testing is appropriate for them and identify available, dates and locations at --sep--krogerhealth.com/covidtesting--sep--.--sep--Are associate temperature checks required?--sep--We are committed to protecting the health and safety of our associates. We are encouraging our associates to closely monitor their health and if they experience symptoms, including a fever, they should contact their doctor and not come to work. Additionally, we are following local ordinances in cities that mandate employee temperature checks.--sep--Is physical distancing encouraged while shopping?--sep--We are installing plexiglass partitions at many cash registers, to further promote physical distancing. In addition, we are adding educational floor decals to promote physical distancing at check lanes and other counters. We also encourage our customers to practice physical distancing while navigating the shopping aisles. In some cities, we are testing one-way aisles.--sep--Is paid leave being offered for associates affected by COVID-19?--sep--The Kroger Co. has enacted Emergency Leave Guidelines, allowing paid time off for associates diagnosed with COVID-19, placed under mandatory quarantine and paid time off for self-isolation and symptoms as verified by an accredited health care professional. All eligible associates will receive their standard pay for up to two weeks (14 days).--sep--For those affected by COVID-19, the organization has also made available additional resources through our Helping Hands fund to provide financial assistance to associates who face hardship due to COVID-19, including lack of access to childcare and for those considered higher-risk.--sep--Have any associates been diagnosed with COVID-19?--sep--Our stores are coordinating closely with local health departments when we learn of positive COVID-19 cases in our employee base and taking immediate action to support and safeguard our associates and customers. We are acutely aware and responding to the safety needs of our associates across our family of companies.--sep--We will continue to work closely with federal, state and local public health authorities as they work to coordinate our country\u2018s response to flatten the curve and slow the spread of COVID-19.--sep--Has associate business travel been suspended?--sep--At this time, we have extended the suspension of commercial air travel through May 31. We will continue to closely monitor events and adjust our guidance accordingly. In lieu of traveling, we recommend our associates use video or audio conference tools for internal meetings as well as with suppliers and partners. --sep--Additional Questions--sep--How is The Kroger Co. giving back?--sep--The Kroger Family of Companies is also uplifting communities in a variety of ways during this unprecedented time, including:--sep--The Kroger Co. Zero Hunger | Zero Waste Foundation has committed more than $6 million to support our neighbors during the COVID-19 pandemic. These grants are funding local food banks and ensuring children with school closures have access to nutritious meals. Learn more about our community contributions in our recent --sep--press release--sep--.--sep--You can join us in our Zero Hunger | Zero Waste mission by donating today to our Emergency COVID-19 Response Fund either --sep--online--sep-- or by rounding up your purchase to the nearest dollar or committing $1, $5 or $10.--sep--Starting April 24, the Kroger Family of Companies is supporting the CARES Act by temporarily waiving the check-cashing fee for government-issued checks.--sep--Has The Kroger Co. provided any updates on its business guidance?--sep--On April 1, The Kroger Co. filed its annual report on Form 10-K and announced business updates in response to the impact from the novel coronavirus (COVID-19). More information can be found in --sep--our newsroom--sep--. --sep--What is your Blueprint for businesses?--sep--On April 21, we published the first installment of --sep--Sharing What We\u2019ve Learned: A Blueprint for Businesses--sep--, available at --sep--KrogerBlueprint.com--sep--. --sep--Our Blueprint is intended to be a resource for businesses of all sizes and sectors of the economy, providing recommendations, insights, best practices and --sep--downloadable creative assets--sep-- to help businesses navigate the next phase of this unprecedented pandemic.--sep--We will continue to add new information to the Blueprint in the coming days and weeks, so when the timing is right for businesses to safely reopen, we\u2019re all prepared to keep our communities safe and supported, together.--sep--Haven't found what you're looking for?--sep--Visit our--sep-- --sep--Help Center--sep-- --sep--for additional assistance. If you would like to speak with us directly, or if this is urgent, please call us at: 1-800-KRO-GERS (--sep--1-800-576-4377--sep--)--sep-- --sep--Connect With Us:--sep--Download the App:--sep--ABOUT THE COMPANY--sep--About the Company--sep--Advertise With Us--sep--Careers--sep--Community--sep--Express HR--sep--Investor Relations--sep--Kroger Real Estate--sep--News Room--sep--Vendors & Suppliers--sep--COMMUNITY--sep--Kroger Community Rewards--sep--Honoring Our Heroes--sep--Sustainability--sep--Request a Donation--sep--CUSTOMER SERVICE--sep--FAQs--sep--Contact Us--sep--Customer Comments--sep--Digital Coupons Policy--sep--My Prescriptions FAQs--sep--Recall Alerts--sep--Feedback--sep--SERVICES--sep--Deli/Bakery Ordering--sep--Digital Coupons--sep--Gift Card Mall--sep--Join Our Customer Panel--sep--Mobile App--sep--Receipt Survey Invitation--sep--Recipes--sep--Shopping List--sep--Store Locator--sep--Weekly Ad--sep--Money Services--sep--GET THE CARD--sep--Learn More--sep--Save on Fuel--sep--Earn Free Groceries--sep--Manage My Card--sep--All Contents \u00a9--sep--2020--sep-- --sep--The Kroger Co.--sep-- --sep--All Rights Reserved--sep--If you are using a screen reader and having difficulty with this website, please call\u00a0--sep--1\u2012800\u2012576\u20124377--sep--.--sep--Pharmacy Privacy Notice--sep--Terms and Conditions--sep--Privacy Policy--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n", "retailer": "kroger"}
{"website": "http://web.archive.org/web/20200603141918id_/https://www.kroger.com/hc/help/faqs/covid-19/general", "text": "\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--Kroger - COVID-19 FAQs--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--Skip to content--sep--Search--sep--Clear--sep--Ship to--sep--\u00a0--sep--94102--sep-- --sep--Locations--sep--Sign In--sep--Cart--sep--Gift Cards--sep--Lists--sep--Weekly Ad--sep--Digital Coupons--sep--Our Payment Cards--sep--Help--sep--Breadcrumb--sep--Help Center--sep--FAQs--sep--COVID-19 - General--sep--General FAQs--sep--COVID-19--sep--General--sep--COVID-19--sep--General--sep--Questions and Answers--sep--Expand All--sep--Are you limiting customer capacity in stores?--sep--As an essential business, we are committed to doing our part to flatten the curve while providing our customers with access to fresh, affordable food. To further encourage physical distancing, we will begin limiting the number of people in our stores at a time to 50% or more of the building code\u2019s calculated capacity. QueVision, our industry-leading technology system that uses sensors and predictive analytics, will help us to monitor traffic flow in and out of the store.--sep--What happens if a store reaches capacity?--sep--Over the last few weeks, customers\u2019 shopping patterns and frequency have changed, so we do not anticipate our stores reaching capacity often. When and if it happens, QueVision will alert us and an associate will direct customers to form a line outside the store, encouraging six feet between each customer. As customers exit the store, additional customers will be able to enter the store. --sep--Are you limiting purchase quantities?--sep--We have set purchase limits on certain categories of items that are in high demand. These purchase limits will also be applied to orders placed on our app or website. This is to ensure that all customers have access to the items they need most.--sep--Will you have special hours for senior citizens?--sep--In some areas, we\u2019re now opening one hour early, to enable senior citizens and other high-risk groups to shop before we open to the public. We\u2019ll continue to evaluate these special hours and make changes as we learn more. You can find the most up-to-date information about your store --sep--here--sep--. --sep--How are you maintaining product availability?--sep--Our supply chain associates are working tirelessly to replenish our stores daily with the items our customers need most. --sep--Has your return policy changed?--sep--For health and safety reasons, we are not currently accepting returns on items purchased in excess that our customers no longer want.--sep--Why did store hours change?--sep--Our modified store hours give our associates the time they need to clean and restock shelves. You can find more information --sep--here--sep--.  --sep--What are you doing to increase pickup and delivery availability?--sep--We\u2019re making more timeslots available to accommodate the increase in demand for our pickup and delivery services. We\u2019ll continue to monitor and make changes as necessary to make pickup and delivery more accessible for our customers.--sep--Does your website show current product inventory?--sep--Pickup & Delivery:--sep-- Inventory varies by store and changes throughout the day as customers shop in-store and online. Inventory is not updated in real time. If an item shows that it\u2019s available for pickup or delivery, availability is not guaranteed. --sep--Ship:--sep-- Our shippable inventory is updated in near-real time. We encourage customers to check our app or website to view item availability. --sep--Unfortunately, our Customer Connect associates do not have insight into item availability. Our app or website is the best source for this information.--sep--What are you doing to protect and support your associates during this time?--sep--The past few weeks have been unprecedented for our country, our associates and our customers. Associates in our stores, warehouses, distribution centers, food production facilities and offices are working around the clock to keep our stores clean, open and stocked.--sep--On March 14, we created a policy allowing paid time off for associates diagnosed with COVID-19 or placed under quarantine. All eligible associates will receive their standard pay for up to 14 days. We have also made additional financial resources available through our --sep--Helping Hands--sep-- fund.  --sep--Can I have groceries delivered to my home without coming into contact with a shopper or driver?--sep--Yes, this option is available at online checkout on delivery orders. Simply choose the --sep--Leave at My Door--sep-- option and check the box next to \"I accept that I do not need to be present when my groceries are delivered.\u201d--sep--Why has the rain check policy been suspended?--sep--Due to current and ongoing product availability issues, we are not able to guarantee in-stock conditions on many items. We will not be issuing rain checks on out-of-stock items until further notice. We appreciate your understanding as we work to keep your store clean, open and stocked to the best of our abilities during this time.--sep--Preparedness, Store Conditions and Products--sep--How is The Kroger Co. handling this unprecedented pandemic?--sep--Our task force has coordinated organizational activities to help our business navigate through this public health event and quickly activate our COVID-19 preparedness plan. We also continue to partner with and follow guidance from federal, state and local agencies, including the CDC and other health organizations.--sep--What shopping options are currently available?--sep--Our associates are working to ensure our in-store, pickup, delivery and ship services are operational and available to customers. --sep--Have stores reduced their operating hours?--sep--In some areas, we have adjusted store operating hours to allow our associates more time to rest, clean and stock. You can view our updated operating hours --sep--here--sep--.--sep--Have stores implemented special operating hours for seniors and higher-risk populations?--sep--We appreciate the concern and care our customers are expressing for senior shoppers and higher-risk customers. All customers deserve to have access to affordable, fresh food and essentials. We're offering special hours for senior shoppers in several cities across the country. We have also been inspired to see local communities working together to shop on behalf of seniors and other higher-risk customers.--sep--We are asking our customers be patient, to be kind to one another and our associates, and to shop responsibly and purchase what you need, knowing that we will continue to replenish stores daily with the supplies and products our customers need most. --sep--Are you waiving check-cashing fees?--sep--Starting April 24, the Kroger Family of Companies is supporting the CARES Act by temporarily waiving the check-cashing fee for government-issued checks. --sep--Are customers required to wear masks?--sep--We encourage all our customers to wear a mask when they visit our stores.--sep--Is free pickup service being offered?--sep--Our purpose is to Feed the Human Spirit, and we are always here for our customers and communities when they need us most, especially in times of uncertainty. --sep--We have experienced an increase in demand for our pickup service as customers seek alternative ways to shop for groceries. So, starting March 23, we are temporarily waiving our pickup service fee nationwide (a value of $4.95), with no minimum order threshold. Because of the surge, our customers may experience limited inventory options and longer wait times than usual. We appreciate our customers\u2019 understanding as we work tirelessly to serve the community during this unprecedented time. --sep--Can customers use SNAP benefits for pickup?--sep--The Kroger Family of Companies has rolled out the acceptance of Supplemental Nutrition Assistance Program (SNAP) benefits for Pickup across the country, with an estimated completion by the end of April. The low-contact, convenient service allows customers to shop online for groceries and pick up their order curbside.--sep-- How Pickup Works:--sep--Choose your preferred store location online or via the app--sep--Shop and place your order for groceries online or via the app--sep--Select a pickup date and time and SNAP/EBT as the payment method. If you\u2019re using an EBT card, you\u2019ll present your payment method at the time of pick up--sep--An associate shops for your order--sep--When it\u2019s time to pick up your order, look for the pickup signs in the store\u2019s parking lot and pull into your parking spot then call the number on the sign to let an associate know you\u2019ve arrived--sep--An associate will bring your order out and load it into your car. At this time, EBT card customers can complete their transaction via a mobile point-of-sale system and pay for ineligible EBT purchases or any remaining balance with their debit or credit card--sep--What about pickup-only stores?--sep--We continue to experience an increase in demand for our pickup service as customers seek alternative ways to shop for groceries. To support the increase, Kroger introduced its first pickup-only location in Cincinnati on March 25. --sep--Customers can select the Mt. Carmel Kroger (4630 Aicholtz Road, Cincinnati) as their preferred pickup location when placing their order on --sep--kroger.com--sep-- or through the app. Pickup will be available from 8 a.m. to 8 p.m. daily. As the location will no longer offer in-store shopping, associates will be fully focused on fulfilling pickup orders. The store\u2019s pharmacy will remain open and customers can speak directly with health care staff or pick up prescriptions. --sep--Are stores offering contact-free checkout options?--sep--To help customers shop safely and quickly, we are in the process of rolling out the improved Scan, Bag, Go mobile app nationwide. Customers using the feature can bring their clean reusable bags to the store where permissible \u2013 or use bags available at the store \u2013 to shop, scan and bag their groceries as they go. When a customer completes their shopping trip, they can pay with their phone, allowing them to bypass the traditional checkout process.--sep--Kroger Pay--sep-- is another capability within the mobile app that provides a contactless payment solution, simplifying the checkout and payment process for customers. The capability is available in several markets.--sep--We also offer a no-contact delivery option, low-contact pickup service and ship-to-home offering for pantry essentials.--sep--Have stores implemented product purchase limits?--sep--We have implemented product purchase limits on highly popular products to help ensure all our customers have access to them. Our manufacturing plants and suppliers are working tirelessly to help replenish our inventories. --sep--Should customers anticipate increased product prices?--sep--We are committed to customers having access to fresh and affordable food. Because of increased demand and limited inventory of some products, customers may experience price increases on commodities like eggs and meat.--sep--Is there a new return policy?--sep--We are temporarily suspending product returns to protect the health and wellbeing of our associates, customers and communities during the COVID-19 pandemic. If any fresh produce, meat, seafood or deli product does not meet our Fresh for Everyone standard, we will replace it or issue a refund. You can learn more about our return policy --sep--here--sep--. --sep--Can customers bring reusable bags?--sep--We continue to allow our customers to use reusable shopping bags, provided there is not a state or local ordinance that prohibits use. --sep--Should customers be concerned about the transmission of COVID-19 through food?--sep--The health and wellbeing of our associates, customers and communities is our top priority. The CDC has not provided guidance that food is a vehicle for virus transmission. If the CDC provides new guidance, we will follow it.--sep--What about the transmission of COVID-19 through imported goods?--sep--Most of our products are domestically sourced. Additionally, there\u2019s no evidence at this time of any coronavirus diagnoses related to imported goods.--sep--How does The Kroger Co. anticipate this event impacting its business?--sep--It\u2019s too early to tell the effect on our business. The event is not currently included in our guidance for 2020. Relative to others in the market we have limited supply chain exposure in China as most of the product we source is domestic.--sep--Are you hiring?--sep--The Kroger Co. has recently provided new career opportunities to more than 100,000 workers nationwide, including those from the hardest-hit sectors like restaurants, hotels and food service distributors. We plan to hire additional workers over the next several weeks to help us to continue to provide fresh food and useful supplies to communities across the country during the COVID-19 pandemic. Candidates may apply via --sep--jobs.kroger.com--sep-- and could be placed for employment within several days of applying. Kroger\u2019s average hourly wage is $15 an hour. And with comprehensive benefits factored in, our average hourly rate is over $20.--sep--Health and Wellbeing--sep--How are associates being recognized and rewarded?--sep--On March 21, we announced a one-time bonus for every hourly frontline grocery, supply chain, manufacturing and customer service associate, amounting to $300 for every full-time associate and $150 for every part-time associate.--sep--On March 31, we announced an additional Hero Bonus for all hourly frontline associates \u2013 a $2 premium above their standard base rate of pay, applied to hours worked March 29 through April 18. The premium will be disbursed weekly to ensure associates have access to additional cash.--sep--On April 16, we announced the extension of our Hero Bonus for all hourly frontline associates through May 2.--sep--On May 1, we extended our Hero Bonus for all hourly frontline associates through May 16. --sep--On May 15, we announced a new $130 million investment in Thank You Pay for all hourly frontline associates, amounting to $400 for qualified full-time associates and $200 for qualified part-time associates. Thank You Pay will be disbursed in two installments on May 30 and June 18.--sep--What are you doing to protect customers and associates?--sep--We are taking these steps to protect our customers and associates: --sep--In Our Stores--sep--Cleaning commonly used areas more often, including cashier stations, self-checkouts, credit card terminals, conveyor belts and food service counters, and cleaning shelves when restocking products.--sep--Sanitizing restrooms more frequently and restocking with supplies, including soap, paper towels and hand sanitizer.--sep--Adding extra hand sanitizer at cashier stations, food service counters, and all Pharmacy, The Little Clinic and Starbucks locations.--sep--Wiping down shopping carts, baskets and equipment. --sep--Partnering with our suppliers to replenish high-demand preparedness products.--sep--Continuing to provide our customers with free disinfectant wipes at our store entrances to sanitize their shopping carts or baskets.--sep--Expanding contact-free payment solutions like Scan, Bag, Go and --sep--Kroger Pay--sep--.--sep--Offering a no-contact delivery option, low-contact pickup service and ship-to-home orders.--sep--Maintaining industry-leading best practices for safe food handling. --sep--Airing a healthy habits message via in-store radio to encourage customers to practice good hygiene and social distancing. --sep--Testing one-way aisles in select markets to its effectiveness as a measure to further support physical distancing. --sep--Limiting the number of customers in our stores to no more than 50% of the building\u2019s maximum capacity. In areas where mandated, we will follow the local and/or state agency\u2019s guidance.--sep--For Our Customers--sep--Encouraging our customers and associates to follow the CDC's suggested hygiene practices to reduce the spread of the virus.--sep--Recommending that our customers also practice safe food handling at home.--sep--Encouraging customers to wear masks in stores, or alternatively, use ecommerce services.--sep--For Our Associates --sep--Supplying and requiring our associates to wear protective masks.--sep--Joining the UFCW--sep-- in calling on federal and state government leaders to take swift action to designate associates at grocery stores as \"extended first responders\" or \"emergency personnel\" to help receive priority access to protective masks and other benefits.--sep--Continuing the use of plexiglass partitions and physical distancing floor decals to promote physical distancing at check lanes and other counters.--sep--Encouraging our associates to closely monitor their health and if they exhibit flu-like symptoms (fever, cough, sore throat, body aches, headache, chills, and fatigue) at work, they should go home and contact their doctor. If an associate has flu-like symptoms at home, they should not come to work. --sep--Continuing to enact our Emergency Leave Guidelines, allowing paid time off for associates diagnosed with COVID-19, placed under mandatory quarantine by their medical provider because of COVID-19 and paid time off for self-isolation and symptoms as verified by an accredited health care professional. All eligible associates will receive their standard pay for up to two weeks (14 days).--sep--Offering $5 million through the Kroger Family of Companies Helping Hands fund to provide financial assistance to associates who face hardship due to COVID-19, including childcare costs.--sep--Providing access to mental health services and other benefits to support associates' mental and physical well-being during this stressful time. We\u2019re also offering an associate hotline to ensure benefit questions are answered quickly.--sep--Extending our work-from-home policy for all associates in our corporate and division offices until at least May 31. We will continue to closely evaluate and adjust our policies accordingly. When the time is right to safely reopen our offices, it will be through a phased approach. --sep--Offering COVID-19 testing to associates--sep-- based on symptoms and medical need.--sep--Providing comprehensive benefits packages, including healthcare coverage and retirement benefits.--sep--Are associates required to wear personal protective equipment (PPE)?--sep--As an essential business, we\u2019ve been balancing our most urgent priority to provide a safe environment for our associates and customers with open stores, ecommerce solutions and an efficiently operating supply chain, so that our communities always have access to fresh, affordable food and products. --sep--We have provided masks for all our store associates to wear, and starting on April 26, we\u2019ll be requiring associates to wear them, in locations where they are not already mandated. Our associates are also welcome to bring their own suitable masks or facial coverings to work, if they prefer.--sep--We recognize that some associates, due to medical reasons or other circumstances, may not be able to wear a mask. Such situations will be addressed on a case-by-case basis. We are sourcing face shields to provide to those associates and will also explore other potential options, as needed.--sep--We also continue to enhance our daily sanitation practices, including cleaning commonly used areas more often like cashier stations, self-checkouts, credit card terminals, food service counters and shelves. --sep--We\u2019ve installed plexiglass partitions at many check lanes, including pharmacy and Starbucks registers, to further promote physical distancing. In addition, we\u2019ve installed educational floor decals to promote physical distancing at check lanes and other counters. --sep--Additionally, we\u2019ve adjusted store operating hours across the country to allow more time for our associates to rest, clean and replenish inventory.--sep--We believe all these steps will help to ensure the safety of our associates and help our communities to flatten the curve while at the same time meeting our obligation to be there for our customers.  --sep--Are Pharmacy and The Little Clinic locations being managed differently?--sep--Because many of our pharmacy or The Little Clinic customers may be visiting us for treatment of an illness, or to fill a prescription for one, our clinics and pharmacies are kept on separate air filtration systems from the rest of the store, which safeguards against germs potentially being spread around the rest of the store, and keeps fresh air circulating throughout. In addition, pharmacies and clinics are always set apart from fresh food areas, such as produce, bakery, and meat and seafood.--sep--All our pharmacists, technicians, clinicians, and patient care technicians follow the strictest rules of infection control. All pharmacies and clinics are cleaned routinely throughout the day with hospital grade sanitation products. During times of extraordinary concern, additional measures are taken.--sep--Are Kroger Family of Pharmacies or The Little Clinic locations offering COVID-19 drive-thru testing?--sep--On April 27, --sep--Kroger Health announced plans--sep-- to expand its drive-thru COVID-19 testing model to 50 locations in more than 12 states to perform up to 100,000 tests by the end of May.--sep--As of May 27, we have formed partnerships with local and state offices and groups in 13 states (Arizona, California, Colorado, Indiana, Kentucky, Michigan, North Carolina, Ohio, South Carolina, Tennessee, Texas, Washington and Wisconsin) to support drive-thru COVID-19 testing.--sep--Americans can access Kroger Health\u2019s free virtual screening tool to determine if testing is appropriate for them and identify available, dates and locations at  --sep--krogerhealth.com/covidtesting--sep--.--sep--On May 4, we announced the continued protection of our frontline associates by making free COVID-19 testing available, based on symptoms and medical need. Learn more --sep--here--sep--.--sep--How many COVID-19 tests have you conducted?--sep--As of May 27, Kroger Health has performed more than 57,000 tests. --sep--Are stores requiring associate temperature checks?--sep--We are encouraging our associates to closely monitor their health and take their temperature at home prior to coming to work. If they experience symptoms, including a fever, they are encouraged to contact their doctor and stay home. Under our --sep--expanded COVID-19 emergency leave guidelines--sep--, associates self-isolating or experiencing symptoms as verified by an accredited health care professional are eligible to receive their standard pay for up to two weeks (14 days).--sep--We started testing temperature checks in our supply chain (distribution centers) several weeks ago and have now expanded associate temperature checks to our stores. We are following local ordinances in cities that mandate employee temperature checks. Associates may also request to have their temperature taken at work. --sep--Are stores encouraging physical distancing while shopping?--sep--We have installed plexiglass partitions at many cash registers, to further promote physical distancing. In addition, we have added educational floor decals to promote physical distancing at check lanes and other counters. We also encourage our customers to practice physical distancing while navigating the shopping aisles. In some cities, we are testing one-way aisles. --sep--Is paid leave being offered for associates affected by COVID-19?--sep--The Kroger Co. has enacted Emergency Leave Guidelines, allowing paid time off for associates diagnosed with COVID-19, placed under mandatory quarantine and paid time off for self-isolation and symptoms as verified by an accredited health care professional. All eligible associates will receive their standard pay for up to two weeks (14 days).--sep--For those affected by COVID-19, the organization has also made available additional resources through our Helping Hands fund to provide financial assistance to associates who face hardship due to COVID-19, including lack of access to childcare and for those considered higher-risk.--sep--Have any associates been diagnosed with COVID-19?--sep--Our stores are coordinating closely with local health departments when we learn of positive COVID-19 cases in our employee base and taking immediate action to support and safeguard our associates and customers. We are acutely aware and responding to the safety needs of our associates across our family of companies.--sep--We will continue to work closely with federal, state and local public health authorities as they work to coordinate our country\u2018s response to flatten the curve and slow the spread of COVID-19.--sep--Has associate business travel been suspended?--sep--At this time, we have extended the suspension of commercial air travel through May 31. We will continue to closely monitor events and adjust our guidance accordingly. In lieu of traveling, we recommend our associates use video or audio conference tools for internal meetings as well as with suppliers and partners. --sep--Additional Questions--sep--How is The Kroger Co. giving back?--sep--The Kroger Family of Companies is also uplifting communities in a variety of ways during this unprecedented time, including:--sep--The Kroger Co. Zero Hunger | Zero Waste Foundation has committed more than $8 million to support our neighbors during the COVID-19 pandemic. These grants are funding local food banks and ensuring children with school closures have access to nutritious meals. Learn more about our community contributions in our recent --sep--press release--sep--.--sep--You can join us in our Zero Hunger | Zero Waste mission by donating today to our Emergency COVID-19 Response Fund either --sep--online--sep-- or by rounding up your purchase to the nearest dollar or committing $1, $5 or $10.--sep--Starting April 24, the Kroger Family of Companies is supporting the CARES Act by temporarily waiving the check-cashing fee for government-issued checks.--sep--Has The Kroger Co. provided any updates on its business guidance?--sep--On April 1, The Kroger Co. filed its annual report on Form 10-K and announced business updates in response to the impact from the novel coronavirus (COVID-19). More information can be found in --sep--our newsroom--sep--. --sep--What is your Blueprint for businesses?--sep--On April 21, we published the first installment of --sep--Sharing What We\u2019ve Learned: A Blueprint for Businesses--sep--, available at --sep--KrogerBlueprint.com--sep--. --sep--Our Blueprint is intended to be a resource for businesses of all sizes and sectors of the economy, providing recommendations, insights, best practices and --sep--downloadable creative assets--sep-- to help businesses navigate the next phase of this unprecedented pandemic.--sep--We will continue to add new information to the Blueprint in the coming days and weeks, so when the timing is right for businesses to safely reopen, we\u2019re all prepared to keep our communities safe and supported, together.--sep--Haven't found what you're looking for?--sep--Visit our--sep-- --sep--Help Center--sep-- --sep--for additional assistance. If you would like to speak with us directly, or if this is urgent, please call us at: 1-800-KRO-GERS (--sep--1-800-576-4377--sep--)--sep-- --sep--Connect With Us:--sep--Download the App:--sep--ABOUT THE COMPANY--sep--About the Company--sep--Advertise With Us--sep--Careers--sep--Community--sep--Express HR--sep--Investor Relations--sep--Kroger Real Estate--sep--News Room--sep--Vendors & Suppliers--sep--COMMUNITY--sep--Kroger Community Rewards--sep--Honoring Our Heroes--sep--Sustainability--sep--Request a Donation--sep--CUSTOMER SERVICE--sep--FAQs--sep--Contact Us--sep--Customer Comments--sep--Digital Coupons Policy--sep--My Prescriptions FAQs--sep--Recall Alerts--sep--Feedback--sep--SERVICES--sep--Deli/Bakery Ordering--sep--Digital Coupons--sep--Gift Card Mall--sep--Join Our Customer Panel--sep--Mobile App--sep--Receipt Survey Invitation--sep--Recipes--sep--Shopping List--sep--Store Locator--sep--Weekly Ad--sep--Money Services--sep--GET THE CARD--sep--Learn More--sep--Save on Fuel--sep--Earn Free Groceries--sep--Manage My Card--sep--All Contents \u00a9--sep--2020--sep-- --sep--The Kroger Co.--sep-- --sep--All Rights Reserved--sep--If you are using a screen reader and having difficulty with this website, please call\u00a0--sep--1\u2012800\u2012576\u20124377--sep--.--sep--Pharmacy Privacy Notice--sep--Terms and Conditions--sep--Privacy Policy--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n", "retailer": "kroger"}
{"website": "http://web.archive.org/web/20200614120807id_/https://www.kroger.com/hc/help/faqs/covid-19/general", "text": "\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--Kroger - COVID-19 FAQs--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--Skip to content--sep--Sign In--sep--Popular--sep--Buy 6, Save $.50--sep--Ways to Shop--sep--Weekly Ad--sep--Digital Coupons--sep--My Prescriptions--sep--Departments--sep--Summer Shop--sep--At Home--sep--Father's Day Shop--sep--Graduation Shop--sep--Meat and Seafood--sep--Fresh Fruit and Vegetables--sep--Pantry--sep--Natural and Organic--sep--Dairy and Eggs--sep--Floral--sep--Frozen--sep--Deli--sep--Bakery--sep--Beer, Wine and Liquor--sep--Candy--sep--Home and Electronics--sep--Cleaning and Household--sep--Health and Wellness--sep--Beauty--sep--Personal Care--sep--Vitamins and Supplements--sep--Baby--sep--Pet--sep--Ship to Home--sep--Specialty Diets--sep--International Cuisine--sep--Fred Meyer Jewelers--sep--Savings--sep--Our Brands--sep--Discover--sep--Pharmacy and Health--sep--Payments and Services--sep--Search--sep--Clear--sep--Ship to--sep--\u00a0--sep--95050--sep-- --sep--Locations--sep--Sign In--sep--Cart--sep--Gift Cards--sep--Lists--sep--Weekly Ad--sep--Digital Coupons--sep--Our Payment Cards--sep--Help--sep--Breadcrumb--sep--Help Center--sep--FAQs--sep--COVID-19 - General--sep--General FAQs--sep--COVID-19--sep--General--sep--COVID-19--sep--General--sep--Questions and Answers--sep--Expand All--sep--Are you limiting customer capacity in stores?--sep--As an essential business, we are committed to doing our part to flatten the curve while providing our customers with access to fresh, affordable food. To further encourage physical distancing, we will begin limiting the number of people in our stores at a time to 50% or more of the building code\u2019s calculated capacity. QueVision, our industry-leading technology system that uses sensors and predictive analytics, will help us to monitor traffic flow in and out of the store.--sep--What happens if a store reaches capacity?--sep--Over the last few weeks, customers\u2019 shopping patterns and frequency have changed, so we do not anticipate our stores reaching capacity often. When and if it happens, QueVision will alert us and an associate will direct customers to form a line outside the store, encouraging six feet between each customer. As customers exit the store, additional customers will be able to enter the store. --sep--Are you limiting purchase quantities?--sep--We have set purchase limits on certain categories of items that are in high demand. These purchase limits will also be applied to orders placed on our app or website. This is to ensure that all customers have access to the items they need most.--sep--Will you have special hours for senior citizens?--sep--In some areas, we\u2019re now opening one hour early, to enable senior citizens and other high-risk groups to shop before we open to the public. We\u2019ll continue to evaluate these special hours and make changes as we learn more. You can find the most up-to-date information about your store --sep--here--sep--. --sep--How are you maintaining product availability?--sep--Our supply chain associates are working tirelessly to replenish our stores daily with the items our customers need most. --sep--Has your return policy changed?--sep--For health and safety reasons, we are not currently accepting returns on items purchased in excess that our customers no longer want.--sep--Why did store hours change?--sep--Our modified store hours give our associates the time they need to clean and restock shelves. You can find more information --sep--here--sep--.  --sep--What are you doing to increase pickup and delivery availability?--sep--We\u2019re making more timeslots available to accommodate the increase in demand for our pickup and delivery services. We\u2019ll continue to monitor and make changes as necessary to make pickup and delivery more accessible for our customers.--sep--Does your website show current product inventory?--sep--Pickup & Delivery:--sep-- Inventory varies by store and changes throughout the day as customers shop in-store and online. Inventory is not updated in real time. If an item shows that it\u2019s available for pickup or delivery, availability is not guaranteed. --sep--Ship:--sep-- Our shippable inventory is updated in near-real time. We encourage customers to check our app or website to view item availability. --sep--Unfortunately, our Customer Connect associates do not have insight into item availability. Our app or website is the best source for this information.--sep--What are you doing to protect and support your associates during this time?--sep--The past few weeks have been unprecedented for our country, our associates and our customers. Associates in our stores, warehouses, distribution centers, food production facilities and offices are working around the clock to keep our stores clean, open and stocked.--sep--On March 14, we created a policy allowing paid time off for associates diagnosed with COVID-19 or placed under quarantine. All eligible associates will receive their standard pay for up to 14 days. We have also made additional financial resources available through our --sep--Helping Hands--sep-- fund.  --sep--Can I have groceries delivered to my home without coming into contact with a shopper or driver?--sep--Yes, this option is available at online checkout on delivery orders. Simply choose the --sep--Leave at My Door--sep-- option and check the box next to \"I accept that I do not need to be present when my groceries are delivered.\u201d--sep--Why has the rain check policy been suspended?--sep--Due to current and ongoing product availability issues, we are not able to guarantee in-stock conditions on many items. We will not be issuing rain checks on out-of-stock items until further notice. We appreciate your understanding as we work to keep your store clean, open and stocked to the best of our abilities during this time.--sep--Preparedness, Store Conditions and Products--sep--How is The Kroger Co. handling this unprecedented pandemic?--sep--Our task force has coordinated organizational activities to help our business navigate through this public health event and quickly activate our COVID-19 preparedness plan. We also continue to partner with and follow guidance from federal, state and local agencies, including the CDC and other health organizations.--sep--What shopping options are currently available?--sep--Our associates are working to ensure our in-store, pickup, delivery and ship services are operational and available to customers. --sep--Have stores reduced their operating hours?--sep--In some areas, we have adjusted store operating hours to allow our associates more time to rest, clean and stock. You can view our updated operating hours --sep--here--sep--.--sep--Have stores implemented special operating hours for seniors and higher-risk populations?--sep--We appreciate the concern and care our customers are expressing for senior shoppers and higher-risk customers. All customers deserve to have access to affordable, fresh food and essentials. We're offering special hours for senior shoppers in several cities across the country. We have also been inspired to see local communities working together to shop on behalf of seniors and other higher-risk customers.--sep--We are asking our customers be patient, to be kind to one another and our associates, and to shop responsibly and purchase what you need, knowing that we will continue to replenish stores daily with the supplies and products our customers need most. --sep--Are you waiving check-cashing fees?--sep--Starting April 24, the Kroger Family of Companies is supporting the CARES Act by temporarily waiving the check-cashing fee for government-issued checks. --sep--Are customers required to wear masks?--sep--We encourage all our customers to wear a mask when they visit our stores.--sep--Is free pickup service being offered?--sep--Our purpose is to Feed the Human Spirit, and we are always here for our customers and communities when they need us most, especially in times of uncertainty. --sep--We have experienced an increase in demand for our pickup service as customers seek alternative ways to shop for groceries. So, starting March 23, we are temporarily waiving our pickup service fee nationwide (a value of $4.95), with no minimum order threshold. Because of the surge, our customers may experience limited inventory options and longer wait times than usual. We appreciate our customers\u2019 understanding as we work tirelessly to serve the community during this unprecedented time. --sep--Can customers use SNAP benefits for pickup?--sep--The Kroger Family of Companies has rolled out the acceptance of Supplemental Nutrition Assistance Program (SNAP) benefits for Pickup across the country, with an estimated completion by the end of April. The low-contact, convenient service allows customers to shop online for groceries and pick up their order curbside.--sep-- How Pickup Works:--sep--Choose your preferred store location online or via the app--sep--Shop and place your order for groceries online or via the app--sep--Select a pickup date and time and SNAP/EBT as the payment method. If you\u2019re using an EBT card, you\u2019ll present your payment method at the time of pick up--sep--An associate shops for your order--sep--When it\u2019s time to pick up your order, look for the pickup signs in the store\u2019s parking lot and pull into your parking spot then call the number on the sign to let an associate know you\u2019ve arrived--sep--An associate will bring your order out and load it into your car. At this time, EBT card customers can complete their transaction via a mobile point-of-sale system and pay for ineligible EBT purchases or any remaining balance with their debit or credit card--sep--What about pickup-only stores?--sep--We continue to experience an increase in demand for our pickup service as customers seek alternative ways to shop for groceries. To support the increase, Kroger introduced its first pickup-only location in Cincinnati on March 25. --sep--Customers can select the Mt. Carmel Kroger (4630 Aicholtz Road, Cincinnati) as their preferred pickup location when placing their order on --sep--kroger.com--sep-- or through the app. Pickup will be available from 8 a.m. to 8 p.m. daily. As the location will no longer offer in-store shopping, associates will be fully focused on fulfilling pickup orders. The store\u2019s pharmacy will remain open and customers can speak directly with health care staff or pick up prescriptions. --sep--Are stores offering contact-free checkout options?--sep--To help customers shop safely and quickly, we are in the process of rolling out the improved Scan, Bag, Go mobile app nationwide. Customers using the feature can bring their clean reusable bags to the store where permissible \u2013 or use bags available at the store \u2013 to shop, scan and bag their groceries as they go. When a customer completes their shopping trip, they can pay with their phone, allowing them to bypass the traditional checkout process.--sep--Kroger Pay--sep-- is another capability within the mobile app that provides a contactless payment solution, simplifying the checkout and payment process for customers. The capability is available in several markets.--sep--We also offer a no-contact delivery option, low-contact pickup service and ship-to-home offering for pantry essentials.--sep--Have stores implemented product purchase limits?--sep--We have implemented product purchase limits on highly popular products to help ensure all our customers have access to them. Our manufacturing plants and suppliers are working tirelessly to help replenish our inventories. --sep--Should customers anticipate increased product prices?--sep--We are committed to customers having access to fresh and affordable food. Because of increased demand and limited inventory of some products, customers may experience price increases on commodities like eggs and meat.--sep--Is there a new return policy?--sep--We are temporarily suspending product returns to protect the health and wellbeing of our associates, customers and communities during the COVID-19 pandemic. If any fresh produce, meat, seafood or deli product does not meet our Fresh for Everyone standard, we will replace it or issue a refund. You can learn more about our return policy --sep--here--sep--. --sep--Can customers bring reusable bags?--sep--We continue to allow our customers to use reusable shopping bags, provided there is not a state or local ordinance that prohibits use. --sep--Should customers be concerned about the transmission of COVID-19 through food?--sep--The health and wellbeing of our associates, customers and communities is our top priority. The CDC has not provided guidance that food is a vehicle for virus transmission. If the CDC provides new guidance, we will follow it.--sep--What about the transmission of COVID-19 through imported goods?--sep--Most of our products are domestically sourced. Additionally, there\u2019s no evidence at this time of any coronavirus diagnoses related to imported goods.--sep--How does The Kroger Co. anticipate this event impacting its business?--sep--It\u2019s too early to tell the effect on our business. The event is not currently included in our guidance for 2020. Relative to others in the market we have limited supply chain exposure in China as most of the product we source is domestic.--sep--Are you hiring?--sep--The Kroger Co. has recently provided new career opportunities to more than 100,000 workers nationwide, including those from the hardest-hit sectors like restaurants, hotels and food service distributors. We plan to hire additional workers over the next several weeks to help us to continue to provide fresh food and useful supplies to communities across the country during the COVID-19 pandemic. Candidates may apply via --sep--jobs.kroger.com--sep-- and could be placed for employment within several days of applying. Kroger\u2019s average hourly wage is $15 an hour. And with comprehensive benefits factored in, our average hourly rate is over $20.--sep--Health and Wellbeing--sep--How are associates being recognized and rewarded?--sep--On March 21, we announced a one-time bonus for every hourly frontline grocery, supply chain, manufacturing and customer service associate, amounting to $300 for every full-time associate and $150 for every part-time associate.--sep--On March 31, we announced an additional Hero Bonus for all hourly frontline associates \u2013 a $2 premium above their standard base rate of pay, applied to hours worked March 29 through April 18. The premium will be disbursed weekly to ensure associates have access to additional cash.--sep--On April 16, we announced the extension of our Hero Bonus for all hourly frontline associates through May 2.--sep--On May 1, we extended our Hero Bonus for all hourly frontline associates through May 16. --sep--On May 15, we announced a new $130 million investment in Thank You Pay for all hourly frontline associates, amounting to $400 for qualified full-time associates and $200 for qualified part-time associates. Thank You Pay will be disbursed in two installments on May 30 and June 18.--sep--What are you doing to protect customers and associates?--sep--We are taking these steps to protect our customers and associates: --sep--In Our Stores--sep--Cleaning commonly used areas more often, including cashier stations, self-checkouts, credit card terminals, conveyor belts and food service counters, and cleaning shelves when restocking products.--sep--Sanitizing restrooms more frequently and restocking with supplies, including soap, paper towels and hand sanitizer.--sep--Adding extra hand sanitizer at cashier stations, food service counters, and all Pharmacy, The Little Clinic and Starbucks locations.--sep--Wiping down shopping carts, baskets and equipment. --sep--Partnering with our suppliers to replenish high-demand preparedness products.--sep--Continuing to provide our customers with free disinfectant wipes at our store entrances to sanitize their shopping carts or baskets.--sep--Expanding contact-free payment solutions like Scan, Bag, Go and --sep--Kroger Pay--sep--.--sep--Offering a no-contact delivery option, low-contact pickup service and ship-to-home orders.--sep--Maintaining industry-leading best practices for safe food handling. --sep--Airing a healthy habits message via in-store radio to encourage customers to practice good hygiene and social distancing. --sep--Testing one-way aisles in select markets to its effectiveness as a measure to further support physical distancing. --sep--Limiting the number of customers in our stores to no more than 50% of the building\u2019s maximum capacity. In areas where mandated, we will follow the local and/or state agency\u2019s guidance.--sep--For Our Customers--sep--Encouraging our customers and associates to follow the CDC's suggested hygiene practices to reduce the spread of the virus.--sep--Recommending that our customers also practice safe food handling at home.--sep--Encouraging customers to wear masks in stores, or alternatively, use ecommerce services.--sep--For Our Associates --sep--Supplying and requiring our associates to wear protective masks.--sep--Joining the UFCW--sep-- in calling on federal and state government leaders to take swift action to designate associates at grocery stores as \"extended first responders\" or \"emergency personnel\" to help receive priority access to protective masks and other benefits.--sep--Continuing the use of plexiglass partitions and physical distancing floor decals to promote physical distancing at check lanes and other counters.--sep--Encouraging our associates to closely monitor their health and if they exhibit flu-like symptoms (fever, cough, sore throat, body aches, headache, chills, and fatigue) at work, they should go home and contact their doctor. If an associate has flu-like symptoms at home, they should not come to work. --sep--Continuing to enact our Emergency Leave Guidelines, allowing paid time off for associates diagnosed with COVID-19, placed under mandatory quarantine by their medical provider because of COVID-19 and paid time off for self-isolation and symptoms as verified by an accredited health care professional. All eligible associates will receive their standard pay for up to two weeks (14 days).--sep--Offering $5 million through the Kroger Family of Companies Helping Hands fund to provide financial assistance to associates who face hardship due to COVID-19, including childcare costs.--sep--Providing access to mental health services and other benefits to support associates' mental and physical well-being during this stressful time. We\u2019re also offering an associate hotline to ensure benefit questions are answered quickly.--sep--Extending our work-from-home policy for all associates in our corporate and division offices until at least May 31. We will continue to closely evaluate and adjust our policies accordingly. When the time is right to safely reopen our offices, it will be through a phased approach. --sep--Offering COVID-19 testing to associates--sep-- based on symptoms and medical need.--sep--Providing comprehensive benefits packages, including healthcare coverage and retirement benefits.--sep--Are associates required to wear personal protective equipment (PPE)?--sep--As an essential business, we\u2019ve been balancing our most urgent priority to provide a safe environment for our associates and customers with open stores, ecommerce solutions and an efficiently operating supply chain, so that our communities always have access to fresh, affordable food and products. --sep--We have provided masks for all our store associates to wear, and starting on April 26, we\u2019ll be requiring associates to wear them, in locations where they are not already mandated. Our associates are also welcome to bring their own suitable masks or facial coverings to work, if they prefer.--sep--We recognize that some associates, due to medical reasons or other circumstances, may not be able to wear a mask. Such situations will be addressed on a case-by-case basis. We are sourcing face shields to provide to those associates and will also explore other potential options, as needed.--sep--We also continue to enhance our daily sanitation practices, including cleaning commonly used areas more often like cashier stations, self-checkouts, credit card terminals, food service counters and shelves. --sep--We\u2019ve installed plexiglass partitions at many check lanes, including pharmacy and Starbucks registers, to further promote physical distancing. In addition, we\u2019ve installed educational floor decals to promote physical distancing at check lanes and other counters. --sep--Additionally, we\u2019ve adjusted store operating hours across the country to allow more time for our associates to rest, clean and replenish inventory.--sep--We believe all these steps will help to ensure the safety of our associates and help our communities to flatten the curve while at the same time meeting our obligation to be there for our customers.  --sep--Are Pharmacy and The Little Clinic locations being managed differently?--sep--Because many of our pharmacy or The Little Clinic customers may be visiting us for treatment of an illness, or to fill a prescription for one, our clinics and pharmacies are kept on separate air filtration systems from the rest of the store, which safeguards against germs potentially being spread around the rest of the store, and keeps fresh air circulating throughout. In addition, pharmacies and clinics are always set apart from fresh food areas, such as produce, bakery, and meat and seafood.--sep--All our pharmacists, technicians, clinicians, and patient care technicians follow the strictest rules of infection control. All pharmacies and clinics are cleaned routinely throughout the day with hospital grade sanitation products. During times of extraordinary concern, additional measures are taken.--sep--Are Kroger Family of Pharmacies or The Little Clinic locations offering COVID-19 drive-thru testing?--sep--On April 27, --sep--Kroger Health announced plans--sep-- to expand its drive-thru COVID-19 testing model to 50 locations in more than 12 states to perform up to 100,000 tests by the end of May.--sep--As of May 27, we have formed partnerships with local and state offices and groups in 13 states (Arizona, California, Colorado, Indiana, Kentucky, Michigan, North Carolina, Ohio, South Carolina, Tennessee, Texas, Washington and Wisconsin) to support drive-thru COVID-19 testing.--sep--Americans can access Kroger Health\u2019s free virtual screening tool to determine if testing is appropriate for them and identify available, dates and locations at  --sep--krogerhealth.com/covidtesting--sep--.--sep--On May 4, we announced the continued protection of our frontline associates by making free COVID-19 testing available, based on symptoms and medical need. Learn more --sep--here--sep--.--sep--How many COVID-19 tests have you conducted?--sep--As of May 27, Kroger Health has performed more than 57,000 tests. --sep--Are stores requiring associate temperature checks?--sep--We are encouraging our associates to closely monitor their health and take their temperature at home prior to coming to work. If they experience symptoms, including a fever, they are encouraged to contact their doctor and stay home. Under our --sep--expanded COVID-19 emergency leave guidelines--sep--, associates self-isolating or experiencing symptoms as verified by an accredited health care professional are eligible to receive their standard pay for up to two weeks (14 days).--sep--We started testing temperature checks in our supply chain (distribution centers) several weeks ago and have now expanded associate temperature checks to our stores. We are following local ordinances in cities that mandate employee temperature checks. Associates may also request to have their temperature taken at work. --sep--Are stores encouraging physical distancing while shopping?--sep--We have installed plexiglass partitions at many cash registers, to further promote physical distancing. In addition, we have added educational floor decals to promote physical distancing at check lanes and other counters. We also encourage our customers to practice physical distancing while navigating the shopping aisles. In some cities, we are testing one-way aisles. --sep--Is paid leave being offered for associates affected by COVID-19?--sep--The Kroger Co. has enacted Emergency Leave Guidelines, allowing paid time off for associates diagnosed with COVID-19, placed under mandatory quarantine and paid time off for self-isolation and symptoms as verified by an accredited health care professional. All eligible associates will receive their standard pay for up to two weeks (14 days).--sep--For those affected by COVID-19, the organization has also made available additional resources through our Helping Hands fund to provide financial assistance to associates who face hardship due to COVID-19, including lack of access to childcare and for those considered higher-risk.--sep--Have any associates been diagnosed with COVID-19?--sep--Our stores are coordinating closely with local health departments when we learn of positive COVID-19 cases in our employee base and taking immediate action to support and safeguard our associates and customers. We are acutely aware and responding to the safety needs of our associates across our family of companies.--sep--We will continue to work closely with federal, state and local public health authorities as they work to coordinate our country\u2018s response to flatten the curve and slow the spread of COVID-19.--sep--Has associate business travel been suspended?--sep--At this time, we have extended the suspension of commercial air travel through May 31. We will continue to closely monitor events and adjust our guidance accordingly. In lieu of traveling, we recommend our associates use video or audio conference tools for internal meetings as well as with suppliers and partners. --sep--Additional Questions--sep--How is The Kroger Co. giving back?--sep--The Kroger Family of Companies is also uplifting communities in a variety of ways during this unprecedented time, including:--sep--The Kroger Co. Zero Hunger | Zero Waste Foundation has committed more than $8 million to support our neighbors during the COVID-19 pandemic. These grants are funding local food banks and ensuring children with school closures have access to nutritious meals. Learn more about our community contributions in our recent --sep--press release--sep--.--sep--You can join us in our Zero Hunger | Zero Waste mission by donating today to our Emergency COVID-19 Response Fund either --sep--online--sep-- or by rounding up your purchase to the nearest dollar or committing $1, $5 or $10.--sep--Starting April 24, the Kroger Family of Companies is supporting the CARES Act by temporarily waiving the check-cashing fee for government-issued checks.--sep--Has The Kroger Co. provided any updates on its business guidance?--sep--On April 1, The Kroger Co. filed its annual report on Form 10-K and announced business updates in response to the impact from the novel coronavirus (COVID-19). More information can be found in --sep--our newsroom--sep--. --sep--What is your Blueprint for businesses?--sep--On April 21, we published the first installment of --sep--Sharing What We\u2019ve Learned: A Blueprint for Businesses--sep--, available at --sep--KrogerBlueprint.com--sep--. --sep--Our Blueprint is intended to be a resource for businesses of all sizes and sectors of the economy, providing recommendations, insights, best practices and --sep--downloadable creative assets--sep-- to help businesses navigate the next phase of this unprecedented pandemic.--sep--We will continue to add new information to the Blueprint in the coming days and weeks, so when the timing is right for businesses to safely reopen, we\u2019re all prepared to keep our communities safe and supported, together.--sep--Haven't found what you're looking for?--sep--Visit our--sep-- --sep--Help Center--sep-- --sep--for additional assistance. If you would like to speak with us directly, or if this is urgent, please call us at: 1-800-KRO-GERS (--sep--1-800-576-4377--sep--)--sep-- --sep--Connect With Us:--sep--Download the App:--sep--ABOUT THE COMPANY--sep--About the Company--sep--Advertise With Us--sep--Careers--sep--Community--sep--Express HR--sep--Investor Relations--sep--Kroger Real Estate--sep--News Room--sep--Vendors & Suppliers--sep--COMMUNITY--sep--Kroger Community Rewards--sep--Honoring Our Heroes--sep--Sustainability--sep--Request a Donation--sep--CUSTOMER SERVICE--sep--FAQs--sep--Contact Us--sep--Customer Comments--sep--Digital Coupons Policy--sep--My Prescriptions FAQs--sep--Recall Alerts--sep--Feedback--sep--SERVICES--sep--Deli/Bakery Ordering--sep--Digital Coupons--sep--Gift Card Mall--sep--Join Our Customer Panel--sep--Mobile App--sep--Receipt Survey Invitation--sep--Recipes--sep--Shopping List--sep--Store Locator--sep--Weekly Ad--sep--Money Services--sep--GET THE CARD--sep--Learn More--sep--Save on Fuel--sep--Earn Free Groceries--sep--Manage My Card--sep--All Contents \u00a9--sep--2020--sep-- --sep--The Kroger Co.--sep-- --sep--All Rights Reserved--sep--If you are using a screen reader and having difficulty with this website, please call\u00a0--sep--1\u2012800\u2012576\u20124377--sep--.--sep--Pharmacy Privacy Notice--sep--Terms and Conditions--sep--Privacy Policy--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n", "retailer": "kroger"}
{"website": "http://web.archive.org/web/20200617040834id_/https://www.kroger.com/hc/help/faqs/covid-19/general", "text": "\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--Kroger - COVID-19 FAQs--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--\n--sep--Skip to content--sep--Sign In--sep--Popular--sep--Buy 6, Save $.50--sep--Father's Day--sep--Weekly Ad--sep--Digital Coupons--sep--My Prescriptions--sep--Departments--sep--Summer Shop--sep--At Home--sep--Father's Day Shop--sep--Graduation Shop--sep--Meat and Seafood--sep--Fresh Fruit and Vegetables--sep--Pantry--sep--Natural and Organic--sep--Dairy and Eggs--sep--Floral--sep--Frozen--sep--Deli--sep--Bakery--sep--Beer, Wine and Liquor--sep--Candy--sep--Home and Electronics--sep--Cleaning and Household--sep--Health and Wellness--sep--Beauty--sep--Personal Care--sep--Vitamins and Supplements--sep--Baby--sep--Pet--sep--Ship to Home--sep--Specialty Diets--sep--International Cuisine--sep--Fred Meyer Jewelers--sep--Savings--sep--Our Brands--sep--Discover--sep--Pharmacy and Health--sep--Payments and Services--sep--Search--sep--Clear--sep--Ship to--sep--\u00a0--sep--95050--sep-- --sep--Locations--sep--Sign In--sep--Cart--sep--Gift Cards--sep--Lists--sep--Weekly Ad--sep--Digital Coupons--sep--Our Payment Cards--sep--Help--sep--Breadcrumb--sep--Help Center--sep--FAQs--sep--COVID-19 - General--sep--General FAQs--sep--COVID-19--sep--General--sep--COVID-19--sep--General--sep--Questions and Answers--sep--Expand All--sep--Are you limiting customer capacity in stores?--sep--As an essential business, we are committed to doing our part to flatten the curve while providing our customers with access to fresh, affordable food. To further encourage physical distancing, we will begin limiting the number of people in our stores at a time to 50% or more of the building code\u2019s calculated capacity. QueVision, our industry-leading technology system that uses sensors and predictive analytics, will help us to monitor traffic flow in and out of the store.--sep--What happens if a store reaches capacity?--sep--Over the last few weeks, customers\u2019 shopping patterns and frequency have changed, so we do not anticipate our stores reaching capacity often. When and if it happens, QueVision will alert us and an associate will direct customers to form a line outside the store, encouraging six feet between each customer. As customers exit the store, additional customers will be able to enter the store. --sep--Are you limiting purchase quantities?--sep--We have set purchase limits on certain categories of items that are in high demand. These purchase limits will also be applied to orders placed on our app or website. This is to ensure that all customers have access to the items they need most.--sep--Will you have special hours for senior citizens?--sep--In some areas, we\u2019re now opening one hour early, to enable senior citizens and other high-risk groups to shop before we open to the public. We\u2019ll continue to evaluate these special hours and make changes as we learn more. You can find the most up-to-date information about your store --sep--here--sep--. --sep--How are you maintaining product availability?--sep--Our supply chain associates are working tirelessly to replenish our stores daily with the items our customers need most. --sep--Has your return policy changed?--sep--For health and safety reasons, we are not currently accepting returns on items purchased in excess that our customers no longer want.--sep--Why did store hours change?--sep--Our modified store hours give our associates the time they need to clean and restock shelves. You can find more information --sep--here--sep--.  --sep--What are you doing to increase pickup and delivery availability?--sep--We\u2019re making more timeslots available to accommodate the increase in demand for our pickup and delivery services. We\u2019ll continue to monitor and make changes as necessary to make pickup and delivery more accessible for our customers.--sep--Does your website show current product inventory?--sep--Pickup & Delivery:--sep-- Inventory varies by store and changes throughout the day as customers shop in-store and online. Inventory is not updated in real time. If an item shows that it\u2019s available for pickup or delivery, availability is not guaranteed. --sep--Ship:--sep-- Our shippable inventory is updated in near-real time. We encourage customers to check our app or website to view item availability. --sep--Unfortunately, our Customer Connect associates do not have insight into item availability. Our app or website is the best source for this information.--sep--What are you doing to protect and support your associates during this time?--sep--The past few weeks have been unprecedented for our country, our associates and our customers. Associates in our stores, warehouses, distribution centers, food production facilities and offices are working around the clock to keep our stores clean, open and stocked.--sep--On March 14, we created a policy allowing paid time off for associates diagnosed with COVID-19 or placed under quarantine. All eligible associates will receive their standard pay for up to 14 days. We have also made additional financial resources available through our --sep--Helping Hands--sep-- fund.  --sep--Can I have groceries delivered to my home without coming into contact with a shopper or driver?--sep--Yes, this option is available at online checkout on delivery orders. Simply choose the --sep--Leave at My Door--sep-- option and check the box next to \"I accept that I do not need to be present when my groceries are delivered.\u201d--sep--Why has the rain check policy been suspended?--sep--Due to current and ongoing product availability issues, we are not able to guarantee in-stock conditions on many items. We will not be issuing rain checks on out-of-stock items until further notice. We appreciate your understanding as we work to keep your store clean, open and stocked to the best of our abilities during this time.--sep--Preparedness, Store Conditions and Products--sep--How is The Kroger Co. handling this unprecedented pandemic?--sep--Our task force has coordinated organizational activities to help our business navigate through this public health event and quickly activate our COVID-19 preparedness plan. We also continue to partner with and follow guidance from federal, state and local agencies, including the CDC and other health organizations.--sep--What shopping options are currently available?--sep--Our associates are working to ensure our in-store, pickup, delivery and ship services are operational and available to customers. --sep--Have stores reduced their operating hours?--sep--In some areas, we have adjusted store operating hours to allow our associates more time to rest, clean and stock. You can view our updated operating hours --sep--here--sep--.--sep--Have stores implemented special operating hours for seniors and higher-risk populations?--sep--We appreciate the concern and care our customers are expressing for senior shoppers and higher-risk customers. All customers deserve to have access to affordable, fresh food and essentials. We're offering special hours for senior shoppers in several cities across the country. We have also been inspired to see local communities working together to shop on behalf of seniors and other higher-risk customers.--sep--We are asking our customers be patient, to be kind to one another and our associates, and to shop responsibly and purchase what you need, knowing that we will continue to replenish stores daily with the supplies and products our customers need most. --sep--Are you waiving check-cashing fees?--sep--Starting April 24, the Kroger Family of Companies is supporting the CARES Act by temporarily waiving the check-cashing fee for government-issued checks. --sep--Are customers required to wear masks?--sep--We encourage all our customers to wear a mask when they visit our stores.--sep--Is free pickup service being offered?--sep--Our purpose is to Feed the Human Spirit, and we are always here for our customers and communities when they need us most, especially in times of uncertainty. --sep--We have experienced an increase in demand for our pickup service as customers seek alternative ways to shop for groceries. So, starting March 23, we are temporarily waiving our pickup service fee nationwide (a value of $4.95), with no minimum order threshold. Because of the surge, our customers may experience limited inventory options and longer wait times than usual. We appreciate our customers\u2019 understanding as we work tirelessly to serve the community during this unprecedented time. --sep--Can customers use SNAP benefits for pickup?--sep--The Kroger Family of Companies has rolled out the acceptance of Supplemental Nutrition Assistance Program (SNAP) benefits for Pickup across the country, with an estimated completion by the end of April. The low-contact, convenient service allows customers to shop online for groceries and pick up their order curbside.--sep-- How Pickup Works:--sep--Choose your preferred store location online or via the app--sep--Shop and place your order for groceries online or via the app--sep--Select a pickup date and time and SNAP/EBT as the payment method. If you\u2019re using an EBT card, you\u2019ll present your payment method at the time of pick up--sep--An associate shops for your order--sep--When it\u2019s time to pick up your order, look for the pickup signs in the store\u2019s parking lot and pull into your parking spot then call the number on the sign to let an associate know you\u2019ve arrived--sep--An associate will bring your order out and load it into your car. At this time, EBT card customers can complete their transaction via a mobile point-of-sale system and pay for ineligible EBT purchases or any remaining balance with their debit or credit card--sep--What about pickup-only stores?--sep--We continue to experience an increase in demand for our pickup service as customers seek alternative ways to shop for groceries. To support the increase, Kroger introduced its first pickup-only location in Cincinnati on March 25. --sep--Customers can select the Mt. Carmel Kroger (4630 Aicholtz Road, Cincinnati) as their preferred pickup location when placing their order on --sep--kroger.com--sep-- or through the app. Pickup will be available from 8 a.m. to 8 p.m. daily. As the location will no longer offer in-store shopping, associates will be fully focused on fulfilling pickup orders. The store\u2019s pharmacy will remain open and customers can speak directly with health care staff or pick up prescriptions. --sep--Are stores offering contact-free checkout options?--sep--To help customers shop safely and quickly, we are in the process of rolling out the improved Scan, Bag, Go mobile app nationwide. Customers using the feature can bring their clean reusable bags to the store where permissible \u2013 or use bags available at the store \u2013 to shop, scan and bag their groceries as they go. When a customer completes their shopping trip, they can pay with their phone, allowing them to bypass the traditional checkout process.--sep--Kroger Pay--sep-- is another capability within the mobile app that provides a contactless payment solution, simplifying the checkout and payment process for customers. The capability is available in several markets.--sep--We also offer a no-contact delivery option, low-contact pickup service and ship-to-home offering for pantry essentials.--sep--Have stores implemented product purchase limits?--sep--We have implemented product purchase limits on highly popular products to help ensure all our customers have access to them. Our manufacturing plants and suppliers are working tirelessly to help replenish our inventories. --sep--Should customers anticipate increased product prices?--sep--We are committed to customers having access to fresh and affordable food. Because of increased demand and limited inventory of some products, customers may experience price increases on commodities like eggs and meat.--sep--Is there a new return policy?--sep--We are temporarily suspending product returns to protect the health and wellbeing of our associates, customers and communities during the COVID-19 pandemic. If any fresh produce, meat, seafood or deli product does not meet our Fresh for Everyone standard, we will replace it or issue a refund. You can learn more about our return policy --sep--here--sep--. --sep--Can customers bring reusable bags?--sep--We continue to allow our customers to use reusable shopping bags, provided there is not a state or local ordinance that prohibits use. --sep--Should customers be concerned about the transmission of COVID-19 through food?--sep--The health and wellbeing of our associates, customers and communities is our top priority. The CDC has not provided guidance that food is a vehicle for virus transmission. If the CDC provides new guidance, we will follow it.--sep--What about the transmission of COVID-19 through imported goods?--sep--Most of our products are domestically sourced. Additionally, there\u2019s no evidence at this time of any coronavirus diagnoses related to imported goods.--sep--How does The Kroger Co. anticipate this event impacting its business?--sep--It\u2019s too early to tell the effect on our business. The event is not currently included in our guidance for 2020. Relative to others in the market we have limited supply chain exposure in China as most of the product we source is domestic.--sep--Are you hiring?--sep--The Kroger Co. has recently provided new career opportunities to more than 100,000 workers nationwide, including those from the hardest-hit sectors like restaurants, hotels and food service distributors. We plan to hire additional workers over the next several weeks to help us to continue to provide fresh food and useful supplies to communities across the country during the COVID-19 pandemic. Candidates may apply via --sep--jobs.kroger.com--sep-- and could be placed for employment within several days of applying. Kroger\u2019s average hourly wage is $15 an hour. And with comprehensive benefits factored in, our average hourly rate is over $20.--sep--Health and Wellbeing--sep--How are associates being recognized and rewarded?--sep--On March 21, we announced a one-time bonus for every hourly frontline grocery, supply chain, manufacturing and customer service associate, amounting to $300 for every full-time associate and $150 for every part-time associate.--sep--On March 31, we announced an additional Hero Bonus for all hourly frontline associates \u2013 a $2 premium above their standard base rate of pay, applied to hours worked March 29 through April 18. The premium will be disbursed weekly to ensure associates have access to additional cash.--sep--On April 16, we announced the extension of our Hero Bonus for all hourly frontline associates through May 2.--sep--On May 1, we extended our Hero Bonus for all hourly frontline associates through May 16. --sep--On May 15, we announced a new $130 million investment in Thank You Pay for all hourly frontline associates, amounting to $400 for qualified full-time associates and $200 for qualified part-time associates. Thank You Pay will be disbursed in two installments on May 30 and June 18.--sep--What are you doing to protect customers and associates?--sep--We are taking these steps to protect our customers and associates: --sep--In Our Stores--sep--Cleaning commonly used areas more often, including cashier stations, self-checkouts, credit card terminals, conveyor belts and food service counters, and cleaning shelves when restocking products.--sep--Sanitizing restrooms more frequently and restocking with supplies, including soap, paper towels and hand sanitizer.--sep--Adding extra hand sanitizer at cashier stations, food service counters, and all Pharmacy, The Little Clinic and Starbucks locations.--sep--Wiping down shopping carts, baskets and equipment. --sep--Partnering with our suppliers to replenish high-demand preparedness products.--sep--Continuing to provide our customers with free disinfectant wipes at our store entrances to sanitize their shopping carts or baskets.--sep--Expanding contact-free payment solutions like Scan, Bag, Go and --sep--Kroger Pay--sep--.--sep--Offering a no-contact delivery option, low-contact pickup service and ship-to-home orders.--sep--Maintaining industry-leading best practices for safe food handling. --sep--Airing a healthy habits message via in-store radio to encourage customers to practice good hygiene and social distancing. --sep--Testing one-way aisles in select markets to its effectiveness as a measure to further support physical distancing. --sep--Limiting the number of customers in our stores to no more than 50% of the building\u2019s maximum capacity. In areas where mandated, we will follow the local and/or state agency\u2019s guidance.--sep--For Our Customers--sep--Encouraging our customers and associates to follow the CDC's suggested hygiene practices to reduce the spread of the virus.--sep--Recommending that our customers also practice safe food handling at home.--sep--Encouraging customers to wear masks in stores, or alternatively, use ecommerce services.--sep--For Our Associates --sep--Supplying and requiring our associates to wear protective masks.--sep--Joining the UFCW--sep-- in calling on federal and state government leaders to take swift action to designate associates at grocery stores as \"extended first responders\" or \"emergency personnel\" to help receive priority access to protective masks and other benefits.--sep--Continuing the use of plexiglass partitions and physical distancing floor decals to promote physical distancing at check lanes and other counters.--sep--Encouraging our associates to closely monitor their health and if they exhibit flu-like symptoms (fever, cough, sore throat, body aches, headache, chills, and fatigue) at work, they should go home and contact their doctor. If an associate has flu-like symptoms at home, they should not come to work. --sep--Continuing to enact our Emergency Leave Guidelines, allowing paid time off for associates diagnosed with COVID-19, placed under mandatory quarantine by their medical provider because of COVID-19 and paid time off for self-isolation and symptoms as verified by an accredited health care professional. All eligible associates will receive their standard pay for up to two weeks (14 days).--sep--Offering $5 million through the Kroger Family of Companies Helping Hands fund to provide financial assistance to associates who face hardship due to COVID-19, including childcare costs.--sep--Providing access to mental health services and other benefits to support associates' mental and physical well-being during this stressful time. We\u2019re also offering an associate hotline to ensure benefit questions are answered quickly.--sep--Extending our work-from-home policy for all associates in our corporate and division offices until at least May 31. We will continue to closely evaluate and adjust our policies accordingly. When the time is right to safely reopen our offices, it will be through a phased approach. --sep--Offering COVID-19 testing to associates--sep-- based on symptoms and medical need.--sep--Providing comprehensive benefits packages, including healthcare coverage and retirement benefits.--sep--Are associates required to wear personal protective equipment (PPE)?--sep--As an essential business, we\u2019ve been balancing our most urgent priority to provide a safe environment for our associates and customers with open stores, ecommerce solutions and an efficiently operating supply chain, so that our communities always have access to fresh, affordable food and products. --sep--We have provided masks for all our store associates to wear, and starting on April 26, we\u2019ll be requiring associates to wear them, in locations where they are not already mandated. Our associates are also welcome to bring their own suitable masks or facial coverings to work, if they prefer.--sep--We recognize that some associates, due to medical reasons or other circumstances, may not be able to wear a mask. Such situations will be addressed on a case-by-case basis. We are sourcing face shields to provide to those associates and will also explore other potential options, as needed.--sep--We also continue to enhance our daily sanitation practices, including cleaning commonly used areas more often like cashier stations, self-checkouts, credit card terminals, food service counters and shelves. --sep--We\u2019ve installed plexiglass partitions at many check lanes, including pharmacy and Starbucks registers, to further promote physical distancing. In addition, we\u2019ve installed educational floor decals to promote physical distancing at check lanes and other counters. --sep--Additionally, we\u2019ve adjusted store operating hours across the country to allow more time for our associates to rest, clean and replenish inventory.--sep--We believe all these steps will help to ensure the safety of our associates and help our communities to flatten the curve while at the same time meeting our obligation to be there for our customers.  --sep--Are Pharmacy and The Little Clinic locations being managed differently?--sep--Because many of our pharmacy or The Little Clinic customers may be visiting us for treatment of an illness, or to fill a prescription for one, our clinics and pharmacies are kept on separate air filtration systems from the rest of the store, which safeguards against germs potentially being spread around the rest of the store, and keeps fresh air circulating throughout. In addition, pharmacies and clinics are always set apart from fresh food areas, such as produce, bakery, and meat and seafood.--sep--All our pharmacists, technicians, clinicians, and patient care technicians follow the strictest rules of infection control. All pharmacies and clinics are cleaned routinely throughout the day with hospital grade sanitation products. During times of extraordinary concern, additional measures are taken.--sep--Are Kroger Family of Pharmacies or The Little Clinic locations offering COVID-19 drive-thru testing?--sep--On April 27, --sep--Kroger Health announced plans--sep-- to expand its drive-thru COVID-19 testing model to 50 locations in more than 12 states to perform up to 100,000 tests by the end of May.--sep--As of May 27, we have formed partnerships with local and state offices and groups in 13 states (Arizona, California, Colorado, Indiana, Kentucky, Michigan, North Carolina, Ohio, South Carolina, Tennessee, Texas, Washington and Wisconsin) to support drive-thru COVID-19 testing.--sep--Americans can access Kroger Health\u2019s free virtual screening tool to determine if testing is appropriate for them and identify available, dates and locations at  --sep--krogerhealth.com/covidtesting--sep--.--sep--On May 4, we announced the continued protection of our frontline associates by making free COVID-19 testing available, based on symptoms and medical need. Learn more --sep--here--sep--.--sep--How many COVID-19 tests have you conducted?--sep--As of May 27, Kroger Health has performed more than 57,000 tests. --sep--Are stores requiring associate temperature checks?--sep--We are encouraging our associates to closely monitor their health and take their temperature at home prior to coming to work. If they experience symptoms, including a fever, they are encouraged to contact their doctor and stay home. Under our --sep--expanded COVID-19 emergency leave guidelines--sep--, associates self-isolating or experiencing symptoms as verified by an accredited health care professional are eligible to receive their standard pay for up to two weeks (14 days).--sep--We started testing temperature checks in our supply chain (distribution centers) several weeks ago and have now expanded associate temperature checks to our stores. We are following local ordinances in cities that mandate employee temperature checks. Associates may also request to have their temperature taken at work. --sep--Are stores encouraging physical distancing while shopping?--sep--We have installed plexiglass partitions at many cash registers, to further promote physical distancing. In addition, we have added educational floor decals to promote physical distancing at check lanes and other counters. We also encourage our customers to practice physical distancing while navigating the shopping aisles. In some cities, we are testing one-way aisles. --sep--Is paid leave being offered for associates affected by COVID-19?--sep--The Kroger Co. has enacted Emergency Leave Guidelines, allowing paid time off for associates diagnosed with COVID-19, placed under mandatory quarantine and paid time off for self-isolation and symptoms as verified by an accredited health care professional. All eligible associates will receive their standard pay for up to two weeks (14 days).--sep--For those affected by COVID-19, the organization has also made available additional resources through our Helping Hands fund to provide financial assistance to associates who face hardship due to COVID-19, including lack of access to childcare and for those considered higher-risk.--sep--Have any associates been diagnosed with COVID-19?--sep--Our stores are coordinating closely with local health departments when we learn of positive COVID-19 cases in our employee base and taking immediate action to support and safeguard our associates and customers. We are acutely aware and responding to the safety needs of our associates across our family of companies.--sep--We will continue to work closely with federal, state and local public health authorities as they work to coordinate our country\u2018s response to flatten the curve and slow the spread of COVID-19.--sep--Has associate business travel been suspended?--sep--At this time, we have extended the suspension of commercial air travel through May 31. We will continue to closely monitor events and adjust our guidance accordingly. In lieu of traveling, we recommend our associates use video or audio conference tools for internal meetings as well as with suppliers and partners. --sep--Additional Questions--sep--How is The Kroger Co. giving back?--sep--The Kroger Family of Companies is also uplifting communities in a variety of ways during this unprecedented time, including:--sep--The Kroger Co. Zero Hunger | Zero Waste Foundation has committed more than $8 million to support our neighbors during the COVID-19 pandemic. These grants are funding local food banks and ensuring children with school closures have access to nutritious meals. Learn more about our community contributions in our recent --sep--press release--sep--.--sep--You can join us in our Zero Hunger | Zero Waste mission by donating today to our Emergency COVID-19 Response Fund either --sep--online--sep-- or by rounding up your purchase to the nearest dollar or committing $1, $5 or $10.--sep--Starting April 24, the Kroger Family of Companies is supporting the CARES Act by temporarily waiving the check-cashing fee for government-issued checks.--sep--Has The Kroger Co. provided any updates on its business guidance?--sep--On April 1, The Kroger Co. filed its annual report on Form 10-K and announced business updates in response to the impact from the novel coronavirus (COVID-19). More information can be found in --sep--our newsroom--sep--. --sep--What is your Blueprint for businesses?--sep--On April 21, we published the first installment of --sep--Sharing What We\u2019ve Learned: A Blueprint for Businesses--sep--, available at --sep--KrogerBlueprint.com--sep--. --sep--Our Blueprint is intended to be a resource for businesses of all sizes and sectors of the economy, providing recommendations, insights, best practices and --sep--downloadable creative assets--sep-- to help businesses navigate the next phase of this unprecedented pandemic.--sep--We will continue to add new information to the Blueprint in the coming days and weeks, so when the timing is right for businesses to safely reopen, we\u2019re all prepared to keep our communities safe and supported, together.--sep--Haven't found what you're looking for?--sep--Visit our--sep-- --sep--Help Center--sep-- --sep--for additional assistance. If you would like to speak with us directly, or if this is urgent, please call us at: 1-800-KRO-GERS (--sep--1-800-576-4377--sep--)--sep-- --sep--Connect With Us:--sep--Download the App:--sep--ABOUT THE COMPANY--sep--About the Company--sep--Advertise With Us--sep--Careers--sep--Community--sep--Express HR--sep--Investor Relations--sep--Kroger Real Estate--sep--News Room--sep--Vendors & Suppliers--sep--COMMUNITY--sep--Kroger Community Rewards--sep--Honoring Our Heroes--sep--Sustainability--sep--Request a Donation--sep--CUSTOMER SERVICE--sep--FAQs--sep--Contact Us--sep--Customer Comments--sep--Digital Coupons Policy--sep--My Prescriptions FAQs--sep--Recall Alerts--sep--Feedback--sep--SERVICES--sep--Deli/Bakery Ordering--sep--Digital Coupons--sep--Gift Card Mall--sep--Join Our Customer Panel--sep--Mobile App--sep--Receipt Survey Invitation--sep--Recipes--sep--Shopping List--sep--Store Locator--sep--Weekly Ad--sep--Money Services--sep--GET THE CARD--sep--Learn More--sep--Save on Fuel--sep--Earn Free Groceries--sep--Manage My Card--sep--All Contents \u00a9--sep--2020--sep-- --sep--The Kroger Co.--sep-- --sep--All Rights Reserved--sep--If you are using a screen reader and having difficulty with this website, please call\u00a0--sep--1\u2012800\u2012576\u20124377--sep--.--sep--Pharmacy Privacy Notice--sep--Terms an